"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 John chapters 1–4
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1john-1-4.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/1john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/1john.json
- data/commentary/mkt-context/1john.json (existing entries)

Historical setting: Johannine community, ca. 85–95 CE, probably Ephesus.
Primary threat: proto-Docetic secessionists (1:6, 2:19, 4:1-3) who split
the community and denied the full incarnation — possibly Cerinthian in
tendency (Irenaeus Haer. 1.26.1: Christ descended on Jesus at baptism,
departed before the cross). Cultural backdrop: Hellenistic light/darkness
dualism (Qumran 1QS 3-4, Platonic), Roman patronage culture, early Christian
house-church social dynamics, Jewish covenant theology.

Key decisions:
- "liar" characterizations: rhetorical-polemical, naming the epistemological
  claim that spiritual knowledge without ethical practice is definitionally false
- "born of God" / "seed remains": divine-life language placed in new covenant
  indwelling context, not Stoic logos-spermatikos
- agape-definition by event (the cross): distinguishes Johannine ethics from
  Hellenistic virtue-theory and Platonic eros
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOHNI = {
  "1": {
    "2": '<p>The term "eternal life" (<em>zoe aionios</em>) had resonance in both Jewish and Hellenistic contexts: in Second Temple Judaism it was associated with the age to come (Dan 12:2); in Hellenistic philosophy "life" could denote the divine life of logos or nous. John insists the eternal life is not an abstract quality or principle but a person who appeared historically and was witnessed by identifiable people. The eyewitness testimony language (<em>teorakamen</em>, <em>marturomen</em>) follows standard Greco-Roman historiographical conventions in which personal observation (<em>autopsia</em>) was the highest criterion for reliable testimony (Polybius 1.4; Thucydides 1.22). The Docetic position that Christ only "seemed" to appear in flesh would have undermined this entire evidentiary structure.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The Greek <em>koinonia</em> (fellowship) had deep social meaning in the Hellenistic world: the <em>koinonia</em> of business partners bound by shared interest, the political <em>koinonia</em> of citizens in the polis (Aristotle, Politics 1252b), the philosophical <em>koinonia</em> of disciples sharing the teacher\'s way of life. John transfers the term to describe a theocentric community defined not by shared interests or intellectual commitments but by relationship to divine persons — the Father and the Son. This would have been comprehensible to Hellenistic audiences as a community structured by participation in divine life, but with the distinctly Jewish insistence that this God is relational and covenantal rather than an abstract principle.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Joy (<em>chara</em>) as the goal of the moral life was a Hellenistic philosophical category: Aristotle\'s <em>eudaimonia</em> (happiness/flourishing) was achieved through virtuous activity; the Stoic sage attained a joy (the only true good) impervious to external circumstances. John inverts the direction of causation: joy is not achieved through moral effort but received through fellowship with the Father and Son, then communicated by proclamation to the community. The "completeness" (<em>pepleromente</em>) of joy suggests not a maximum emotional intensity but the filling-up of what apostolic proclamation is designed to accomplish — community formed around the life that was from the beginning.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The secessionists apparently claimed profound spiritual fellowship with God while maintaining ethical indifference to their embodied conduct — consistent with proto-Gnostic anthropology: the divine spark (<em>pneuma</em>) within is unaffected by the flesh\'s behavior, and sin is a matter of material existence rather than moral rebellion. This is the first of John\'s six "if we say/claim" conditionals (1:6, 8, 10; 2:4, 6, 9), each targeting a specific slogan of the opponents. The community recognized these as the theological self-descriptions of the secessionists, making the letter in part a close rebuttal of positions the community had heard from departing members.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Claiming sinlessness or moral perfectibility had several cultural homes: Stoic philosophy taught that the sage could achieve rational self-mastery beyond ordinary moral failure; proto-Gnostic anthropology taught that the spiritual person (<em>pneumatikos</em>) was not subject to moral categories that applied to the material (<em>psychikos</em>) person. Some teachers apparently argued that since matter is inherently corrupt, the spiritual person\'s material sins are irrelevant to their spiritual status. John\'s counter designates this not as enlightenment but as self-deception (<em>planomen heautous</em>) — the very error the opponents claimed to have transcended.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The Jewish practice of confession (Yom Kippur communal confession, Ps 32:5, Ps 51) stands behind this verse\'s pastoral instruction. The "faithful and just" (<em>pistos kai dikaios</em>) combines covenant reliability (the Hebrew <em>hesed</em>-faithfulness of God) with righteous judicial procedure: God forgives not by ignoring sin but by doing so righteously — because Christ\'s atonement (2:2) satisfies divine justice. The conditional structure ("if we confess") assumes ongoing need for confession, its iterative verbal aspect contrasting with any claim to have transcended the need for forgiveness through spiritual elevation or direct mystical union with God.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The claim "we have not sinned" makes God a liar because the entire redemptive narrative — the Torah\'s sacrificial system, the prophets\' calls to return, the incarnation as the atoning sacrifice — presupposes universal human sinfulness (Ps 14:3; 1 Kgs 8:46; Eccl 7:20). To deny one\'s own sin is not merely self-deception (v. 8) but an implicit theological claim that contradicts the scriptural testimony about the human condition. In the proto-Docetic context, this may have been tied to the separation of the spiritual self from the sinful flesh: if the true spiritual self is divine, it cannot be said to have sinned in the material domain.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "2": '<p>The term <em>hilasmos</em> (atoning sacrifice) is the Greek equivalent of the Hebrew <em>kipper</em> (to atone) — the Yom Kippur term. In the LXX, <em>hilasmos</em> and <em>hilasterion</em> describe the mercy seat (<em>kapporeth</em>) where the high priest sprinkled blood on the Day of Atonement (Lev 16:14-15). The universality ("not only for ours but also for the sins of the whole world") directly counters any restriction of salvation to the spiritually elite — a characteristic Gnostic move of limiting genuine salvation to the <em>pneumatikoi</em>. John extends the scope of the atonement to the entire world (<em>holos ho kosmos</em>), anchoring it in the historical crucifixion rather than in an abstract spiritual event.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The claim to "know God" (<em>egnokamen auton</em>) was a central proto-Gnostic boast: the Greek <em>gnosis</em> as the means of salvation had permeated Hellenistic culture through Platonic epistemology, mystery cult initiations, and nascent Gnostic systems. John does not deny the category of knowing but redefines its test: the verification of genuine knowledge of God is not mystical illumination, esoteric initiation, or intellectual ascent but ethical obedience to his commands. This was a direct counter to any spirituality that claimed experiential God-knowledge while bypassing the commandments as relevant only to the material rather than spiritual domain.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The "liar" characterization (appearing also in 1:6; 2:22; 4:20) reflects the epistemological stakes of the community crisis rather than mere polemical anger. The secessionists used the language of knowing, seeing, and being in the light — the same vocabulary John uses — but filled it with different content. John\'s sharp label is an epistemological claim: knowledge of God that does not reshape conduct is definitionally not knowledge of the God who is light (1:5), who is love (4:8), and whose commands reflect his character. The "liar" is not morally inferior but epistemologically self-contradicted — claiming to know one whose nature they deny in practice.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The "made complete" (<em>teteleitai</em>) language — brought to its goal, matured — was a Hellenistic philosophical term for the perfection of virtue. Aristotle distinguished virtues in process from those that had reached completion; Philo used <em>teleios</em> of the sage who had reached spiritual maturity. John transfers the category from philosophical perfection to covenantal faithfulness: love for God reaches its <em>telos</em> not through contemplative ascent but through obedient word-keeping. The completion of love in obedience simultaneously verifies genuine knowledge — making the ethical and the epistemological inseparable in Johannine thought.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The "walking as Jesus walked" (<em>peripatein kathos ekeinos periepatesan</em>) creates a biographical criterion for evaluating claimed spiritual experience. In the Hellenistic world, philosophers demonstrated their system\'s validity through their own manner of life — the Stoic sage who practiced apathy, Diogenes the Cynic who lived what he taught, the Epicurean who lived by his master\'s example. John applies this biographical-exemplary logic to Christ: the incarnate life of Jesus — humble service (John 13:1-17), self-giving love (John 15:13), total obedience to the Father — is the norm against which the secessionists\' claims to be "in him" must be measured.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The appeal to "from the beginning" (<em>ap\' arches</em>) grounds the community\'s ethic in the original apostolic deposit rather than in recent revelations or progressive spiritual illumination. Gnostic systems often claimed to possess secret traditions going back further than the public teaching — to Jesus\' private instruction of selected disciples, or to pre-creation gnosis. John counters by locating authority in the community\'s received tradition from the beginning: the old command is the original, the reliable, the authentic. Novelty in teaching marks false teaching, not spiritual advancement; antiquity of tradition marks legitimacy, not obsolescence.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The "new command" is new in the sense of eschatological newness — the Jeremiah 31 new covenant, the Ezekiel 36 new heart, the Johannine community\'s experience of the Spirit\'s indwelling. The light/darkness transition language is not Platonic metaphysics but apocalyptic temporal structure: the ages are turning, and the community lives in the overlap between the passing aeon (darkness) and the arriving one (true light). The command is the same love command but now enacted in the light of the Christ-event, made visible and real in the community\'s actual practice rather than merely aspirational in a community still awaiting the Messiah\'s coming.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Hatred of "a brother or sister" in the Johannine community context likely refers specifically to the schism of 2:19: the secessionists who departed and possibly their contempt for those who remained (viewing them as the spiritually unadvanced). John\'s moral counter is direct: those who claim superior enlightenment while demonstrating contempt for the community they left are still in the darkness they claim to have transcended. Their claimed advancement from the ordinary community to a higher spiritual state is falsified by the behavioral evidence — walking in hatred is walking in darkness, regardless of the spiritual vocabulary used to describe the departure.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The stumbling-block (<em>skandalon</em>) language echoes OT warnings about things that cause Israel to stumble (Ezek 14:3-4; Lev 19:14) and early Christian concern for protecting the weak (Matt 18:6; Rom 14:13). The absence of <em>skandalon</em> in the one who loves has a double reference: internally, their love is genuine and their life non-contradictory; externally, they do not become a stumbling-block to others by schismatic behavior that disrupts the community. Love is the non-skandalon posture — the orientation that avoids both causing harm and embodying the ethical self-contradiction of the secessionists.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Walking (<em>peripatein</em>) in light or darkness is an ethical metaphor with deep Jewish roots (Ps 1:1 "walking in the counsel of the ungodly"; Prov 4:18-19 "the path of the just like shining light") and wide Hellenistic philosophical usage (the virtuous vs. vicious life). At Qumran, the Two Spirits teaching explicitly described the children of darkness as walking in darkness (1QS 3:21), governed by the Angel of Darkness. John\'s readers would have recognized the light/darkness walk as a community-affiliation marker: the love-community (walking in light) vs. the schism-community (claiming light while walking in the hatred that is darkness).</p>',
    "12": '<p>Forgiveness "on account of his name" invokes the Second Temple Jewish understanding of the divine name as the bearer of divine authority and presence (Ex 3:15; Num 6:27). To act "in the name of" someone was to act with their delegated authority. For the early Christian community, forgiveness "in the name of Jesus" (Acts 2:38; 10:43) was the covenantal claim that the authority to forgive sins resided in Jesus. The community\'s assurance of forgiveness rests not on their spiritual state or level of knowledge but on the authority of a name that carries the weight of all that Jesus accomplished in his death and resurrection.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The three-group address (little children, fathers, young men) may reflect generational stratification corresponding to spiritual maturity — a pattern found in Greco-Roman household ethics (Aristotle, Politics 1.5) and early Christian community structures (1 Tim 5:1-2; Tit 2:1-6). The "fathers" who know "him who is from the beginning" (the preexistent Christ of John 1:1) likely represents the community\'s oldest members with the deepest rootedness in the original apostolic tradition. The "young men" who have overcome the evil one are those who have successfully resisted the secessionists\' attraction through the indwelling word.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The indwelling word as the source of strength against the evil one reflects early Christian appropriation of Jewish Torah-devotion language: as the righteous person\'s delight in Torah (Ps 1:2; 119:11 "I have hidden your word in my heart") protected against sin, so the community\'s internalized apostolic word protects against the evil one\'s influence through false teaching. The secessionists, by contrast, were claiming a direct spiritual anointing that bypassed the community\'s received tradition — a claim John addresses in the next section (2:20-27) by asserting that the anointing the community already possesses enables them to know the truth of the original proclamation.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The threefold taxonomy of worldly temptation maps onto recognizable Greco-Roman moral categories: the lust of the flesh (<em>epithumia tes sarkos</em>) was the category of bodily desire that Platonic and Stoic moral philosophy sought to control through reason; the lust of the eyes (<em>epithumia ton ophthalmon</em>) addressed by philosophers from Democritus to Epictetus as covetous desire activated through sight; the pride of life (<em>alazoneia tou biou</em>) was the vainglory of social display criticized by Stoics as a form of false valuation. John does not share the Hellenistic solution (rational control of passion) but his diagnostic categories align with contemporaneous moral discourse.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The transience of the world (<em>kosmos</em>) and its desires was a Stoic philosophical commonplace: Marcus Aurelius meditates repeatedly on the passing of all things (Meditations 4.3, 4.35); Epicureans sought <em>ataraxia</em> (tranquility) in the face of impermanence. John agrees on the transience but locates permanence not in the philosopher\'s inner withdrawal or rational endurance but in the covenant will of God — doing God\'s will is the mode of sharing in the eschatological permanence that outlasts the passing world order. The permanence on offer is not stoic imperturbability but resurrection-life in the age to come.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The anointing (<em>chrisma</em>) from the Holy One — either God or Christ — is John\'s counter to the secessionists\' claimed superior gnosis. In the OT, anointing consecrated kings (1 Sam 16:13), priests (Ex 29:7), and occasionally prophets (1 Kgs 19:16), marking their divine authorization. In early Christianity, the anointing of the Spirit (Acts 10:38; 2 Cor 1:21-22) was understood as the community\'s participation in Christ\'s own anointing. John\'s point is democratizing: the entire community has received the anointing that authenticates genuine knowledge of God — not merely a spiritual elite within it, directly countering any two-tier anthropology (pneumatikoi vs. psychikoi) underlying the secessionists\' position.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The pastoral confidence expressed here — writing to those who already know the truth rather than to those who lack it — is the opposite of Gnostic initiation pedagogy, which communicated secret knowledge to a deficient elect few. John does not offer new revelation but confirms what the community already possesses through the apostolic proclamation. The threat is not ignorance but being led astray from what one already has — which is why the correct pastoral response is confirmation and reminder rather than disclosure of new mysteries. The secessionists were the ones offering the new; John claims to offer nothing but the original.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The denial that "Jesus is the Christ" in the Johannine context is not the Jewish rejection of messianic claims but the proto-Docetic/Cerinthian split: denying that the historical human Jesus is identical with the divine Christ. Cerinthus (Irenaeus Haer. 1.26.1) taught that Christ descended on Jesus at baptism and departed before the crucifixion — making "Jesus" and "the Christ" different entities. This is the specific denial John addresses: the unity of the human Jesus and the divine Christ in a single person is the confession the secessionists have abandoned, probably because their anthropology made a fully incarnate divine person philosophically intolerable.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The inseparability of the Father and the Son was a Jewish-monotheistic claim pressed into Christological service. To deny the Son (the pre-existent Word made flesh, the historical Jesus) is to deny the Father — because the Son is the only one through whom the Father has been disclosed (John 1:18; 14:9). The Cerinthian strategy of affirming a "Father-God" while relativizing the incarnate Son — preserving God\'s transcendence by separating him from the material-historical event of the crucifixion — is precisely the denial John targets: you cannot have the Father on terms other than those the Father himself has established through the Son\'s incarnation, death, and resurrection.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The "remain in" (<em>menein en</em>) language is characteristically Johannine (John 15:4-7; 17:21-23): the mutual abiding of the community in Christ and Christ in the community. The condition for this abiding is that "what you heard from the beginning" — the original apostolic proclamation about the historical Jesus — remains lodged in the community. The secessionists\' departure from the original teaching is not spiritual progress but a departure from the very condition of abiding in the Father and Son. Their new gnosis has broken the connection rather than deepening it — a pattern John identifies throughout the letter.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The "promised eternal life" identifies the community as a covenant people living between promise and fulfillment — a characteristically Jewish temporal structure. The promise of eternal life is the eschatological inheritance that Daniel 12:2 anticipated, that Jesus claimed to give (John 11:25; 17:3), and that the community already has as first-fruits through the Spirit (1 John 5:11-12) but awaits in fullness at the parousia. The promise grounds the community\'s perseverance against the secessionists\' allure: what they hold is not merely present experience but the beginning of what God has pledged in covenant.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The "leading astray" (<em>planonton</em>) places the secessionists in the OT category of false prophets (Jer 23:13-14; Deut 13:5-6 — those who draw Israel after other gods) and the eschatological-deceiver warnings Jesus gave (Matt 24:4, 11, 24). The pastoral identification of schismatic teachers as "those who lead astray" is not merely polemic but community-protection applied from prophetic tradition: the community is warned not merely about intellectual error but about the social-destructive dynamics of schism and the spiritual damage of following teachers whose Christology severs them from the incarnate Son.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The claim that the community "does not need anyone to teach you" besides the anointing must be read against Jeremiah 31:33-34\'s new covenant promise: "I will put my law in their minds... No longer will they teach their neighbor, saying \'Know the LORD,\' because they will all know me." The new covenant promised direct divine instruction through the Spirit — not that human teaching is categorically unnecessary, but that the Spirit\'s anointing equips the community to discern authentic from false teaching. The "anointing teaches" replaces the secessionists as the community\'s interpretive authority, making the community self-sufficient in relation to their claims of superior spiritual access.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The parousia expectation (the coming of Christ) was a near-term hope in early Christianity, providing the eschatological horizon for community ethics. The confidence/shame language (<em>parresia</em> vs. <em>aischunthomen</em>) reflects the honor-shame structure of Mediterranean culture: the parousia is presented as a public event at which the community\'s faithfulness or apostasy will be visible to all. The exhortation to continue in Christ against the pull of the secessionists is grounded in eschatological stakes: what the community holds now determines their standing at the public moment of Christ\'s appearing, when the secessionists\' claims will be adjudicated.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The connection between divine character and community character is covenantal: the children take after the Father. In OT theology, Israel\'s ethical behavior was to reflect the character of their God (Lev 19:2: "Be holy because I, the LORD your God, am holy"; Deut 10:18-19: care for the stranger because God cares for the stranger). John applies this character-inheritance logic to the new covenant community: born of God (<em>gegennetal</em>, perfect tense: the birth has happened with continuing effect), they bear the character of the one from whom they are born — righteousness produces righteousness as a generative fact of the divine nature communicated in new birth.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "2": '<p>The "not yet made known" of the community\'s future state reflects Jewish apocalyptic reserve about the nature of resurrection existence. Paul similarly spoke of the resurrection body as beyond present imagination (1 Cor 15:35-49). The Johannine formulation "we shall be like him, for we shall see him as he is" combines the <em>visio dei</em> tradition (seeing God as the highest eschatological blessing: Ps 17:15; Rev 22:4; Matt 5:8) with a transformation logic: the unveiled vision of Christ reshapes the viewer into his likeness. This has Platonic resonance (Republic 517c — the philosopher-king is transformed by what he contemplates) but is grounded in bodily resurrection rather than intellectual ascent.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Self-purification (<em>hagnizein heauton</em>) in anticipation of encountering the divine echoes Jewish ritual purification (Num 19; Lev 16; Ex 19:10 — purification before the Sinai theophany) but transforms it: the ground of purification is not ritual compliance but the eschatological hope of seeing Christ as he is. The Pharisaic tradition extended priestly purity norms to all Israel as preparation for the kingdom\'s coming. Early Christian communities applied this purification-logic to embodied life (1 Cor 6:19-20; 2 Cor 7:1). The secessionist claim to spiritual purity while indifferent to embodied ethics is the implicit target: genuine hope for the vision of Christ necessarily shapes present embodied conduct.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The "appearance" (<em>ephanerothea</em>) language is the anti-Docetic vocabulary of the letter: Christ appeared in real human form — not seemed to appear or manifested spiritually while remaining non-material. The purpose of the appearance is somatic (to take away sins) and requires real flesh: only a genuine human offering can atone for human sin, which was the logic of the Levitical system (Lev 17:11: "the life of the flesh is in the blood, and I have given it to you to make atonement for yourselves"). The sinlessness of Christ ("in him is no sin") provides the qualification that makes his offering non-defective — unlike animals that could only be physically unblemished, Christ was morally sinless.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The claim that the one who "lives in him" does not keep on sinning (present participle: continuous, habitual practice) must be read against both Gnostic antinomianism (spiritual persons are above moral categories) and any perfectionist misreading (claiming absolute sinlessness, contradicted by 1:8-10). John is describing the directional impossibility of sin as the governing orientation for one born of God — not freedom from individual failures but freedom from sin as the organizing principle of life. The Two Spirits theology of Qumran (1QS 3-4) similarly distinguished the spirit that governs one\'s fundamental orientation from individual moral failures.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The warning against being led astray (<em>planao</em>) grounds righteousness in behavioral evidence rather than spiritual claim. In the Greco-Roman ethical tradition, character (<em>ethos</em>) was disclosed through habitual action (<em>praxis</em>) — Aristotle argued in the Nicomachean Ethics (2.1) that virtue is demonstrated and formed by consistent practice, not by claim or intellectual profession. John applies this ethical realism against the secessionists: righteousness is demonstrated by doing right (<em>ho poion ten dikaiosunen</em>), not by claiming right knowledge or superior spiritual status. The tree is known by its fruit.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The devil as the original sinner is a Second Temple Jewish development of the fallen-angel tradition (1 Enoch 6-16; The Life of Adam and Eve). In these texts, Satan\'s sin preceded and enabled human sin, establishing a genealogy of transgression with a cosmic origin. The Qumran community\'s dualistic anthropology (1QS 3:17-21) placed Belial as the ruler of those walking in darkness, their sinfulness a participation in his cosmic rebellion. John\'s stark "of the devil" characterization identifies persistent sinning not merely as moral failure but as genealogical alignment — belonging to the wrong lineage, participating in a cosmic rebellion whose origin precedes all human history.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The "seed of God" (<em>sperma autou</em>) remaining in the born-of-God person is one of the most interpreted phrases in the letter. The Stoics spoke of the <em>logos spermatikos</em> (generative reason) embedded in all things. In Jewish terms, the divine word/Torah was likened to seed that germinates within the person (Isa 55:10-11; 4 Ezra 9:31). John\'s point: the divine generative principle within the born-of-God person is ontologically incompatible with sin as a continuing orientation — not because the person has achieved perfection (1:8-10 guards against this) but because the divine life communicated in new birth orients them away from sin toward the Father\'s character.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The two-children taxonomy (God\'s children / devil\'s children) echoes the Qumran Two Spirits doctrine (1QS 3-4) and the dualistic moral anthropology of late Second Temple Judaism: the Community of the Covenant saw themselves as children of light while outsiders were children of darkness. John applies this to the immediate community crisis: the visible test of genealogical belonging is ethical — doing right and loving the brother. The schism has made visible which genealogy the secessionists belong to, regardless of their spiritual claims. The community has the discernment tool: character disclosed by behavior, specifically by love for the community members.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The command to love one another (<em>agapao allelous</em>) "from the beginning" connects to John 13:34-35 — the "new commandment" Jesus gave at the Last Supper, defining the community\'s communal identity. The early Christian community was recognized by external observers for its mutual care: Tertullian (Apology 39, ca. 197 CE) reports pagans observing "See how they love one another" as a distinctive social marker. This stood in contrast to the competitive patronage relationships and civic rivalries of Greco-Roman urban society, where love was typically calibrated to social status and benefit exchange.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The world\'s hatred of the community was both an immediate social experience and theologically interpreted. In Ephesus, Christian refusal to participate in the imperial cult, trade guild sacrifices, and civic religious festivals made the community socially suspect and economically marginal. Pliny the Younger\'s letter to Trajan (Ep. 10.96, ca. 112 CE) describes the economic impact of Christian presence: those who sold sacrificial animals reported significant loss of trade. The community\'s hostility from the world was not paranoia but social fact — the "world" John names is the institutional and social structures organized around allegiances incompatible with covenant loyalty to Christ.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Passed from death to life" (<em>metabebakamen ek tou thanatou eis ten zoen</em>) is the community\'s realized eschatology — they experience now what Jewish eschatology expected at the resurrection (Dan 12:2). The Qumran community similarly claimed a present enjoyment of eschatological life (1QH 11:19-23: "You have raised me to an eternal height"). John\'s test for this transition is characteristically ethical rather than experiential: not mystical illumination or esoteric knowledge but the communal love that the Spirit produces. Love is the existential verification of the new life that new birth initiates — verifiable by the community itself as well as by outsiders.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The equivalence of hatred and murder follows the Sermon on the Mount\'s internalization of the sixth commandment (Matt 5:21-22) and the Jewish ethical tradition\'s attention to interior moral states, not merely external actions (Lev 19:17-18 addresses hatred in the heart alongside vengeance in action). The Johannine innovation is the Cain-typology: the hatred within the secessionist party — who hold the "unenlightened" majority community in contempt — is placed in the genealogy of Cain\'s murderous jealousy. This is typological identification: the structure of schismatic contempt mirrors the structure of the first murder (hatred of a brother whose faithfulness God accepted).</p>',
    "16": '<p>The definition of love by historical event rather than philosophical concept is the distinctively Johannine move. In the Hellenistic world, love (<em>eros</em>, <em>philia</em>, <em>agape</em>) was theorized extensively: Plato\'s Symposium offered ascending forms of love from physical desire to contemplation of the Form of Beauty; Aristotle analyzed friendship (<em>philia</em>) as varying grades of mutual benefit. John bypasses all these conceptual frameworks: love is defined by what happened at the crucifixion ("Jesus Christ laid down his life for us"). This event-definition determines what "love one another" means: self-giving to the point of death, not merely benevolent sentiment or calculated mutual benefit.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The economic test of love had deep roots in Jewish tradition: Deut 15:7-11 on opening the hand to the poor; the prophets\' critique of those who neglect the poor (Amos 5:12; Isa 58:7); Prov 19:17 connecting lending to the poor with lending to God. In the Johannine community of Ephesus, economic disparities between wealthy and poor members (common in house-churches hosted by patrons) meant that the love-ethic had immediate material implications. The term "closes his heart" (<em>kleio ta splanchna</em>) uses physiological language: the <em>splanchna</em> (entrails) were the seat of deep emotion in both Greek and Hebrew thought (Hebrew <em>rahamim</em>, "womb-compassion").</p>',
    "18": '<p>The critique of verbal over practical love addresses a specific cultural reality: Greco-Roman rhetoric celebrated the power of speech, and the sophistic tradition held that eloquence marked wisdom. The secessionist teachers may well have been persuasive speakers — John\'s critique is that the ultimate test of love is not eloquence but action. The "in truth" (<em>en aletheia</em>) connects love-in-action to the epistemological framework of the letter: genuine knowledge of God (the truth) is inseparable from genuine practical love, making verbal claims without action epistemologically false (as in 4:20), not merely morally incomplete.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Assurance of belonging to the truth (<em>aletheia</em>) through practical love provides a pastoral epistemology for a community unsettled by the secessionists\' claims to superior spiritual knowledge. The "setting the heart at rest" (<em>peisomen ten kardian hemon</em>) — persuading or stilling the heart — addresses the anxiety that spiritual claims without ethical grounding can generate. John grounds assurance in the practical and verifiable: active love demonstrated in the community is the epistemological basis of belonging to the truth, accessible to every member rather than restricted to those who have received special illumination.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The "condemning heart" is the conscience that accuses — recognized in both Jewish (Eccl 7:20; Job 27:6) and Hellenistic thought (Seneca\'s inner judge, Epistulae 97: "There is a God within us"). The Pauline tradition also addressed the condemning conscience (Rom 8:1; 2 Cor 1:12). John\'s pastoral answer is theocentric: God\'s knowledge is greater than the conscience\'s partial, anxiety-ridden self-assessment. This is not a license to ignore conscience but a specific assurance that God\'s verdict on the person who practices love (even imperfectly) is not determined by the heart\'s condemnation. The context is love-in-action (v. 18), not moral license.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The confidence (<em>parresia</em>) before God echoes the boldness of access described in Hebrews 10:19 and in Jewish texts (Wis 5:1; Job 22:26 LXX: the righteous will lift up their face before God). In the Greco-Roman world, <em>parresia</em> was the freedom of speech in the Athenian assembly — the citizen\'s right to speak openly before the governing body. John transfers the term to the community\'s access to God: those whose practice of love has stilled the condemning conscience approach the divine as those who have standing, not as suppliants hoping for clemency from an unpredictable judge.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The connection between prayer effectiveness and commandment-keeping has deep Jewish covenant roots: Ps 66:18 ("If I had cherished sin in my heart, the Lord would not have listened"), Prov 28:9 ("If anyone turns a deaf ear to instruction, even their prayers are detestable"), Isa 1:15 (God refusing the prayers of those whose hands are full of blood). Prayer and ethics are inseparable in the covenant framework: prayer is not a spiritual technique but the relational address of covenant partners whose relationship with God is shaped by their fidelity. The secessionists\' claims to spiritual closeness with God while neglecting the love-command is precisely the target of this logic.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The double-command structure (faith in the name of Jesus + love for one another) is the Johannine crystallization of the entire ethical demand. In Second Temple Judaism, the Shema (Deut 6:4-5: love God) and Lev 19:18 (love neighbor) were already identified as the Torah\'s summary — the tradition Jesus builds on in Mark 12:29-31. John\'s version replaces abstract love of God with specific faith-commitment to Jesus (giving it Christological precision against the secessionists\' god-without-the-Son) and makes community-love the test and expression of that faith. The two are not merely correlated but constitutively inseparable — the one who separates them (loving "God" while despising the brother) has broken both simultaneously.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The Trinitarian mutuality of indwelling (the community in God, God in the community, verified by the Spirit) connects to the Johannine Farewell Discourse (John 14:16-17, 23; 17:21-23). In Hellenistic terms, the Stoics spoke of the divine <em>logos</em> permeating all things; in Jewish tradition, the Shekinah dwelt among the covenant community (Ex 25:8). John distinguishes the new covenant reality: the Spirit\'s indwelling is not a general divine presence in creation but the specific gift of the eschatological covenant, verifying the community\'s belonging to God through two converging evidences — ethical (keeping commands) and pneumatological (the Spirit given as a present reality).</p>'
  },
  "4": {
    "3": '<p>The failure to "acknowledge Jesus" (the full human name, without the title "Christ") may target those who accept a heavenly Christ-figure while dismissing the historical particularity of the man Jesus. The "spirit of the antichrist" was expected to come in the last days — the eschatological adversary of Jewish apocalyptic (Belial in Qumran; the man of lawlessness in 2 Thess 2) — but is already present in the secessionists\' teaching. The prophetic discernment criterion has shifted from behavioral (OT: does the prophet lead Israel after other gods?) to Christological (early Christianity: does the spirit confess the fully incarnate Christ?), reflecting the new community\'s defining theological boundary.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The community\'s victory over the spirits of error is attributed to the greater Spirit within them rather than to their own discernment or moral achievement. The cosmic battle language (overcoming spirits; greater/lesser power) reflects the apocalyptic worldview shared by Second Temple Judaism (1 Enoch; the Qumran War Scroll 1QM) and early Christianity: behind the human teachers of error are spiritual forces, and the community\'s ability to discern and reject false teaching is not their own achievement but the greater Spirit\'s work. The community is not spiritually outmatched by the secessionists despite the latter\'s sophisticated claims to superior spiritual access.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The secessionists\' success in attracting followers ("the world listens to them") is explained theologically rather than apologetically. Their message resonates with the world because it comes from the world\'s value-system — spiritualized, undemanding of embodied ethics, compatible with Hellenistic dualism that separated material from spiritual, and intellectually sophisticated in ways that appealed to Hellenistic aspirations. This would have been an important pastoral explanation for a disorienting phenomenon: how can teachers who misrepresent Christ attract so many? John\'s answer: their attractiveness is the confirmation of their worldly origin, not evidence of divine authentication.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The appeal to the community\'s reception of apostolic tradition as a discernment criterion inverts the secessionists\' criterion: they likely claimed that their advanced gnosis marked them as from God and that the uncomprehending majority were the spiritually unadvanced. John claims the opposite: those who are of God recognize God\'s voice in the original apostolic proclamation ("we" = the eyewitness community of 1:1-3); those who are not of God do not recognize it. The ecclesiological epistemology: the Spirit who inspired the apostolic testimony enables the community to recognize the apostolic word as true, making the community\'s reception of that word the test rather than the claimant\'s self-assessment.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The theological grounding of love in God\'s character rather than in social obligation, self-interest, or philosophical virtue is the distinctively Johannine contribution to ethical discourse. In Aristotle\'s analysis of friendship (<em>philia</em>), the highest friendship was based on shared virtue (Nicomachean Ethics 8.3). In Stoic ethics, benevolence toward all humans followed from recognizing the divine <em>logos</em> in each. John\'s grounding is categorically different: love does not arise from recognizing the divine in humans but from being born of a God who is love and therefore participating in his character — the source of love is in God\'s being, not in human potential or rational capacity.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"God is love" (<em>ho theos agape estin</em>) is one of the most theologically concentrated statements in the NT. In Greek philosophy, God was identified with various attributes: Plato\'s God was Goodness itself (Republic 508e); Aristotle\'s God was thought thinking itself (Metaphysics 12.9); the Stoics identified God with cosmic Reason (<em>logos</em>). None of these traditions identified God with love as a substantial attribute — love was a passion, and the divine was impassible. John\'s statement is not merely that God acts lovingly but that love is essential to what God is — making those who do not love ontologically disconnected from the source of all love, not merely morally deficient.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The sending of the Son (<em>apostellein ton huion</em>) is the Johannine formulation of the Incarnation as missional event (cf. John 3:16-17). In the context of the letter\'s anti-Docetic polemic, the "sent into the world" language insists on the worldward directionality of the incarnation: the Son did not merely appear to enter the world or manifest spiritually while remaining non-material, but was actually sent into the material creation. The purpose ("that we might live through him") grounds the incarnation in the need for life from a source beyond human capacity — echoing the life-giving function of the Johannine Son (John 10:10; 11:25).</p>',
    "10": '<p>The definition of love as God\'s prior and unconditional action (not our love but his) directly counters any merit-based or mystical-achievement model of the divine-human relationship. In Platonic <em>eros</em>, the soul\'s love for the Beautiful is the upward movement of the desiring soul toward its divine source (Symposium 210a-212b): human love initiates the ascent. In Stoic ethics, love of the divine <em>logos</em> follows from recognizing it within oneself. John\'s <em>agape</em> reverses the direction: divine love descends first to the undeserving, requires no prior human love to activate it, and expresses itself in the costly atoning sacrifice rather than in aesthetic or rational contemplation.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The ethical imperative follows from the indicative of God\'s love-in-Christ with logical (<em>opheilomen</em>: "we owe" — moral obligation, debt language) rather than merely aspirational force. In the Greco-Roman patronage system, receiving a gift created an obligation to return equivalent benefit to the patron. John uses the obligation-logic but transforms it: the recipients of God\'s love cannot repay God directly (he needs nothing from them) but are obligated to extend the same quality of love to one another within the covenant community. The love circulates horizontally within the community because it originates vertically from God.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The invisibility of God (<em>theon oudeis populate teoraken</em>) was a commonplace in Jewish theology (Ex 33:20; John 1:18; Deut 4:12) and Hellenistic philosophy (Plato, Timaeus 28c: the Maker is difficult to find and impossible to communicate). Mystery cult initiates claimed visions of the divine; proto-Gnostic teachers claimed direct access to the hidden God through esoteric knowledge. John\'s theological move is remarkable: the invisible God becomes visible not in mystical visions or esoteric initiation, but in the community\'s practice of love for one another. The mundane social practice of communal love is the locus of divine visibility in the world.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The Spirit as the indwelling verification of the mutual abiding connects to the early Christian understanding of the Spirit as the "down payment" or "seal" of the eschatological inheritance (2 Cor 1:21-22; Eph 1:13-14). In the context of the letter, the community\'s possession of the Spirit is the counterpoint to the secessionists\' claim to superior spiritual insight: both parties claimed the Spirit, but John identifies the authentic Spirit by the Spirit\'s content — the apostolic proclamation of the incarnate Christ (4:2) and the community\'s actual practice of love. The Spirit and ethics mutually verify one another in the Johannine framework.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The "Savior of the world" (<em>Soter tou kosmou</em>) was a title used for Roman emperors in the Hellenistic East — Augustus was celebrated as <em>soter</em> on inscriptions from Asia Minor (Priene inscription, 9 BCE), and the god Asclepius was regularly titled <em>soter</em> for his healing. John\'s application of the title to Jesus is an implicit counter-claim: the one who actually saves the world is not the emperor with his legions and bread distributions or the deity with his temple healings, but the one who laid down his life as the atoning sacrifice for the world\'s sins. The political and religious resonances of the title in Roman Ephesus would not have been missed.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The confession "Jesus is the Son of God" is the Johannine community\'s boundary-marker confession that both the pre-existent divine Son (1:2; John 1:1-14) and the historical human Jesus are one and the same person. Against Cerinthian Christology, which separated Jesus (the human) from the Christ/Son (the divine spirit that descended at baptism), this confession insists on the identity: the Son of God is Jesus — the man born of Mary, crucified under Pilate, raised on the third day. The indwelling relationship (God in them, they in God) is conditioned on this specific Christological precision, not on a vague theism or spirituality that separates the divine Son from the human Jesus.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The "rely on" (<em>pepisteukamen</em>: we have believed and continue to trust, perfect tense indicating past-with-present-consequence) indicates settled confidence grounded in experienced reality rather than mere intellectual assent. The formula "God is love" repeated (first in 4:8) underscores it as the theological center of the section. Living in love (<em>menein en te agape</em>) is the ethically verified form of mystical abiding-language: the community lives in God not through contemplative ascent or esoteric initiation but through the daily practice of the love that God\'s character — disclosed definitively in Christ\'s cross — defines, models, and makes possible by the Spirit\'s indwelling.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The day of judgment as the horizon of community ethics reflects Jewish apocalypticism (the Day of the LORD: Amos 5:18-20; Dan 12:1-2) and early Christian parousia expectation. The confidence (<em>parresia</em>) on the day of judgment is not moral perfection but the standing of those who are "like him in this world" — those formed in Christ\'s image through the Spirit\'s work, verified by their practice of love. The judgment-confidence is not earned through achievement but given to those who abide in love, because their abiding in love is their abiding in the God who is love — whose own character covers and forms them for the eschatological verdict.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Fear as the opposite of love had several cultural locations: in Hellenistic philosophy, fear (<em>phobos</em>) was a passion to be overcome by rational virtue (Stoics) or philosophical friendship (Epicureans). In Jewish covenant theology, fear of God was both a virtue (reverent awe, <em>yir\'at YHWH</em>: Ps 111:10; Prov 1:7) and — in the sense of enslaving dread — a mark of the pre-covenant condition (Deut 28:65-67: unending anxiety as the covenant-breaker\'s fate). John\'s use is specific: the fear "that has to do with punishment" (<em>kolasis</em>) is the anxiety of the one not yet made secure in God\'s love through the atonement — it is the pre-forgiveness orientation, not the reverent awe of the covenant-insider.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The priority of God\'s love in the sequence (he loved first; therefore we love) is both chronological and ontological — human love is derivative, responsive, secondary in nature as well as in time. In the context of the letter, this grounds the community\'s love-practice not in human moral achievement or spiritual advancement but in the received love of God that makes human love possible as a response and participation. The secessionists, by effectively bypassing the significance of the historical cross (the event of God\'s prior love), have cut themselves off from the very source of the love they would need to generate in order to maintain the kind of community that John describes as belonging to God.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The command linking love of God and love of the brother/sister gives the Johannine ethics its structural coherence: the vertical love (toward God) is inseparable from the horizontal (toward the community). This echoes the Shema-Lev 19:18 double summary of Torah and Jesus\' Great Commandment (Mark 12:29-31), applied specifically to the community crisis: one cannot claim to love the invisible God while despising the visible member of the community from whom one has schismed. The command creates a logical impossibility for those who have separated themselves from the Johannine community while claiming superior love of God — their schism is not spiritual advancement but a self-refuting abandonment of the very love they claim to possess.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '1john')
    merge_comm(existing, JOHNI)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1john', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'1 John mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
